Note: ===================================================================
Note: HIR TO HCL GENERATOR
Note: ===================================================================
Note: Generates HCL (HashiCorp Configuration Language) code from Runa HIR
Note: for Terraform and other HashiCorp tools.

Note: Part of the Translation Translation System
Note: Location: compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/hcl/hir_to_hcl.runa
Note: ===================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as ListCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as DictCore

Note: ===================================================================
Note: GENERATION CONTEXT
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Generation context for the legacy line-buffered HCL translator. Stores
indent state and an accumulated list of pre-indented lines.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three fields: indent_level (current depth), indent_string (the unit
indent, defaults to two spaces) and code_buffer (a List of fully-indented
String lines that is joined with newlines by get_generated_code).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
String-concat-per-line approach: O(n) per emit times O(n) lines gives
O(n^2) total. Acceptable for typical Terraform-sized configurations
(hundreds of lines), not for large outputs.
@End Performance_Hints

Type called "HCLGenerationContext":
    indent_level as Integer
    indent_string as Integer
    code_buffer as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Allocate a fresh HCL generation context with default 2-space indent
and an empty code buffer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Constructs HCLGenerationContext with indent_level 0, indent_string "  ",
and a new empty list for code_buffer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_generation_context" returns Integer:
    Let ctx be a value of type HCLGenerationContext with
        indent_level as 0,
        indent_string as "  ",
        code_buffer as proc list_create from ListCore

    Return ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Step into a deeper HCL block (resource body, dynamic block).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Increments ctx.indent_level by 1.
@End Implementation

Process called "increase_indent" takes ctx as Integer:
    Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Step out of an HCL block. Note: does NOT clamp at zero, so callers must
keep the increase/decrease calls balanced.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Decrements ctx.indent_level by 1 unconditionally.
@End Implementation

Process called "decrease_indent" takes ctx as Integer:
    Set ctx.indent_level to ctx.indent_level minus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Build the current indent prefix string by repeating indent_string
indent_level times.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops indent_level times, concatenating indent_string into a result
accumulator. Returns the accumulated String.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) string_concat per call where n is indent_level. Called for every
emitted line which makes overall emission O(N*L) in lines * average
depth.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "get_current_indent" takes ctx as Integer returns Integer:
    Let indent be ""
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than ctx.indent_level:
        Set indent to proc string_concat from StringPrim with indent, ctx.indent_string
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return indent
End Process

@Reasoning:
Append a complete pre-indented line to the buffer. The trailing newline
is NOT included here; get_generated_code joins lines with "\n".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Computes current indent string, concatenates with the line, appends the
result to ctx.code_buffer.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_line" takes ctx as Integer, line as Integer:
    Let indent be proc get_current_indent with ctx
    Let full_line be proc string_concat from StringPrim with indent, line
    proc list_append from ListCore with ctx.code_buffer, full_line
End Process

@Reasoning:
Append an empty line for visual separation between HCL blocks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Appends "" to ctx.code_buffer; the join step will render this as a
bare newline.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_blank_line" takes ctx as Integer:
    proc list_append from ListCore with ctx.code_buffer, ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
Join the accumulated buffer lines into a single newline-separated
String. Called once at the end of translation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates code_buffer, concatenates each line into a result accumulator
with "\n" separators between (no trailing newline after the last line).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(L^2) in line count due to repeated string_concat. Consider migrating
to the byte-buffer emitter for large outputs.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "get_generated_code" takes ctx as Integer returns Integer:
    Let result be ""
    Let count be proc list_length from ListCore with ctx.code_buffer
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than count:
        Let line be proc list_get from ListCore with ctx.code_buffer, i
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, line

        If i is less than count minus 1:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "\n"
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return result
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MAIN GENERATION ENTRY POINT
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public driver for HIR -> HCL translation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates a context, dispatches the HIR module through generate_module,
returns the joined output string.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_hcl_from_hir" takes hir_module as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ctx be proc create_generation_context

    Note: Generate HCL configuration from HIR module
    proc generate_module with ctx, hir_module

    Let hcl_code be proc get_generated_code with ctx
    Return hcl_code
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: MODULE GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Translate the top-level HIR module. HIR module declarations
(classes representing HCL block types, plus top-level variables and
constants) are walked and dispatched to specialised generators.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Iterates the module's declaration list. For class declarations,
dispatches to generate_class_as_block (which switches on the class
kind into resource/variable/output/etc.). For variable and constant
declarations, dispatches to generate_variable_declaration and
generate_constant_declaration respectively.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_module" takes ctx as Integer, hir_module as Integer:
    Let declarations be proc hir_get_declarations from HIR with hir_module
    Let decl_count be proc list_length from ListCore with declarations

    Note: First pass: emit every block (HIR class) and every top-level attribute (a const
    Note: HIR variable that is not a local). Local variables are accumulated for a grouped
    Note: emission so multiple `local x = ...` bindings reconstruct a single locals { } block.
    Let locals be proc list_create from ListCore
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than decl_count:
        Let decl be proc list_get from ListCore with declarations, i
        Let decl_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with decl

        If decl_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CLASS:
            proc generate_class_as_block with ctx, decl
            proc emit_blank_line with ctx
        End If

        If decl_type is equal to HIR.HIR_VARIABLE:
            Let is_local be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with decl, "hcl_local"
            If is_local is equal to 1:
                proc list_append from ListCore with locals, decl
            Otherwise:
                proc generate_variable_declaration with ctx, decl
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Second pass: emit the grouped locals block if any local bindings were collected.
    Let locals_count be proc list_length from ListCore with locals
    If locals_count is greater than 0:
        proc emit_line with ctx, "locals {"
        proc increase_indent with ctx
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than locals_count:
            Let local_decl be proc list_get from ListCore with locals, j
            proc generate_variable_declaration with ctx, local_decl
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        proc decrease_indent with ctx
        proc emit_line with ctx, "}"
        proc emit_blank_line with ctx
    End If
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: CLASS/BLOCK GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
HCL has many block kinds (resource, variable, output, module, provider,
data, terraform, dynamic). Each is encoded as a class declaration in HIR
with a "kind" or stereotype tag; this dispatcher routes to the matching
generate_*_block helper.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Inspects the class's stereotype/kind discriminator and dispatches to the
appropriate generate_*_block proc.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_class_as_block" takes ctx as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Note: Check HCL block type metadata
    Let block_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with class_node, "hcl_block_type"

    If block_type is equal to 0:
        Note: Regular class, skip
        Return 0
    End If

    Let is_resource be proc string_equals from StringCore with block_type, "resource"
    If is_resource is equal to 1:
        proc generate_resource_block with ctx, class_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Let is_variable be proc string_equals from StringCore with block_type, "variable"
    If is_variable is equal to 1:
        proc generate_variable_block with ctx, class_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Let is_output be proc string_equals from StringCore with block_type, "output"
    If is_output is equal to 1:
        proc generate_output_block with ctx, class_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Let is_module be proc string_equals from StringCore with block_type, "module"
    If is_module is equal to 1:
        proc generate_module_block with ctx, class_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Let is_provider be proc string_equals from StringCore with block_type, "provider"
    If is_provider is equal to 1:
        proc generate_provider_block with ctx, class_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Let is_data be proc string_equals from StringCore with block_type, "data"
    If is_data is equal to 1:
        proc generate_data_block with ctx, class_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Let is_terraform be proc string_equals from StringCore with block_type, "terraform"
    If is_terraform is equal to 1:
        proc generate_terraform_block with ctx, class_node
        Return 0
    End If

    Let is_dynamic be proc string_equals from StringCore with block_type, "dynamic"
    If is_dynamic is equal to 1:
        proc generate_dynamic_block with ctx, class_node
        Return 0
    End If
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit a Terraform "resource type name { ... }" block. Used to declare
managed infrastructure resources.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the resource type and name from class metadata, emits the header
line, increases indent, emits body via generate_block_body, decreases
indent, emits closing brace.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_resource_block" takes ctx as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Note: resource "type" "name" { ... }
    Let resource_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with class_node, "hcl_resource_type"
    Let resource_name be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with class_node, "hcl_resource_name"

    Let line be "resource "
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, "\""
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, resource_type
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, "\" \""
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, resource_name
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, "\" {"

    proc emit_line with ctx, line
    proc increase_indent with ctx

    Note: Generate block body (fields)
    proc generate_block_body with ctx, class_node

    proc decrease_indent with ctx
    proc emit_line with ctx, "}"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit a "variable name { ... }" block. Used to declare Terraform input
variables with type and default fields.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the variable name, emits the header, then body via
generate_block_body which translates type/default/description fields.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_variable_block" takes ctx as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Note: variable "name" { ... }
    Let class_name be proc hir_get_class_name from HIR with class_node

    Let line be "variable \""
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, class_name
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, "\" {"

    proc emit_line with ctx, line
    proc increase_indent with ctx

    proc generate_block_body with ctx, class_node

    proc decrease_indent with ctx
    proc emit_line with ctx, "}"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit an "output name { value = ... }" block. Used to expose Terraform
module outputs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the output name, emits the header, then body via
generate_block_body which translates the value expression.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_output_block" takes ctx as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Note: output "name" { ... }
    Let class_name be proc hir_get_class_name from HIR with class_node

    Let line be "output \""
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, class_name
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, "\" {"

    proc emit_line with ctx, line
    proc increase_indent with ctx

    proc generate_block_body with ctx, class_node

    proc decrease_indent with ctx
    proc emit_line with ctx, "}"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit a "module name { source = ... }" block. Used to instantiate
Terraform child modules.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the module instance name, emits the header, body via
generate_block_body for source/version/variable values.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_module_block" takes ctx as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Note: module "name" { ... }
    Let module_name be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with class_node, "hcl_module_name"

    Let line be "module \""
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, module_name
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, "\" {"

    proc emit_line with ctx, line
    proc increase_indent with ctx

    proc generate_block_body with ctx, class_node

    proc decrease_indent with ctx
    proc emit_line with ctx, "}"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit a "provider name { ... }" block. Configures Terraform's provider
plugins (aws, azurerm, kubernetes, ...).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads provider name, emits header, body via generate_block_body for
provider-specific configuration arguments.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_provider_block" takes ctx as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Note: provider "name" { ... }
    Let provider_name be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with class_node, "hcl_provider_name"

    Let line be "provider \""
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, provider_name
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, "\" {"

    proc emit_line with ctx, line
    proc increase_indent with ctx

    proc generate_block_body with ctx, class_node

    proc decrease_indent with ctx
    proc emit_line with ctx, "}"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit a "data type name { ... }" block. Used to fetch existing
infrastructure data for use in Terraform expressions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the data source type and instance name, emits the header, body
via generate_block_body for query arguments.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_data_block" takes ctx as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Note: data "type" "name" { ... }
    Let data_type be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with class_node, "hcl_data_type"
    Let data_name be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with class_node, "hcl_data_name"

    Let line be "data \""
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, data_type
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, "\" \""
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, data_name
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, "\" {"

    proc emit_line with ctx, line
    proc increase_indent with ctx

    proc generate_block_body with ctx, class_node

    proc decrease_indent with ctx
    proc emit_line with ctx, "}"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit a "terraform { ... }" block. Configures the Terraform engine
itself (required_version, backend, etc.).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits the "terraform {" header, body via generate_block_body, then "}".
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_terraform_block" takes ctx as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Note: terraform { ... }
    proc emit_line with ctx, "terraform {"
    proc increase_indent with ctx

    proc generate_block_body with ctx, class_node

    proc decrease_indent with ctx
    proc emit_line with ctx, "}"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit a "dynamic name { ... }" block. Dynamic blocks let Terraform
generate nested configuration via for_each iteration.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the dynamic block name, emits the header, body via
generate_block_body for the for_each / content nested structure.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_dynamic_block" takes ctx as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Note: dynamic "block_name" { ... }
    Let block_name be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with class_node, "hcl_dynamic_block"

    Let line be "dynamic \""
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, block_name
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, "\" {"

    proc emit_line with ctx, line
    proc increase_indent with ctx

    proc generate_block_body with ctx, class_node

    proc decrease_indent with ctx
    proc emit_line with ctx, "}"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit the body of a block: a sequence of "key = value" attribute lines
and nested blocks. Shared by all generate_*_block helpers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walks the class's members list. For property declarations emits
"name = " + expression. For nested class declarations recurses into
generate_class_as_block (for nested blocks like provisioners).
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_block_body" takes ctx as Integer, class_node as Integer:
    Let members be proc hir_get_class_members from HIR with class_node
    Let member_count be proc list_length from ListCore with members
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than member_count:
        Let member be proc list_get from ListCore with members, i
        Let member_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with member

        If member_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FIELD:
            Let field_name be proc hir_get_field_name from HIR with member
            Let initializer be proc hir_get_field_initializer from HIR with member

            If initializer is not equal to 0:
                Let value_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, initializer

                Let attr_line be proc string_concat from StringPrim with field_name, " = "
                Set attr_line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with attr_line, value_str

                proc emit_line with ctx, attr_line
            End If
        End If

        Note: A nested block is a class member; emit "keyword { body }" and recurse.
        If member_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CLASS:
            Let nested_name be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with member, "hcl_nested_name"
            If nested_name is equal to 0:
                Set nested_name to proc hir_get_class_name from HIR with member
            End If

            Let nested_header be proc string_concat from StringPrim with nested_name, " {"
            proc emit_line with ctx, nested_header
            proc increase_indent with ctx
            proc generate_block_body with ctx, member
            proc decrease_indent with ctx
            proc emit_line with ctx, "}"
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: VARIABLE AND CONSTANT GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Emit a top-level HCL "variable name { ... }" block from a HIR variable
declaration. Distinct from generate_variable_block which works from a
class declaration.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads name, type, default value, description from the HIR var node.
Emits a "variable" block with appropriate type, default, and
description attribute lines.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_variable_declaration" takes ctx as Integer, var_node as Integer:
    Let var_name be proc hir_get_variable_name from HIR with var_node
    Let initializer be proc hir_get_variable_initializer from HIR with var_node

    Let value_str be "null"
    If initializer is not equal to 0:
        Set value_str to proc generate_expression with ctx, initializer
    End If

    Let line be proc string_concat from StringPrim with var_name, " = "
    Set line to proc string_concat from StringPrim with line, value_str
    proc emit_line with ctx, line
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: EXPRESSION GENERATION
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Translate an HIR expression to an HCL value expression. HCL supports
literals, references (var.x, local.y, resource_type.name.attr),
function calls, arithmetic and comparison operators, ternary
conditionals, lists, and objects.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dispatches on node_type to emit the corresponding HCL syntax. Literals
are rendered with appropriate quoting; identifiers are emitted bare;
member/index access becomes dotted/bracketed paths.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_expression" takes ctx as Integer, expr_node as Integer returns Integer:
    If expr_node is equal to 0:
        Return "null"
    End If

    Let expr_type be proc hir_node_type from HIR with expr_node

    Note: Integer/float literals are produced by other frontends; HCL's own numbers arrive as
    Note: string literals tagged hcl_number and are handled in the string-literal branch.
    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_INT_LITERAL:
        Let int_value be proc hir_get_int_literal_value from HIR with expr_node
        Return int_value
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_FLOAT_LITERAL:
        Let float_value be proc hir_get_float_literal_value from HIR with expr_node
        Return float_value
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_STRING_LITERAL:
        Let value be proc hir_get_string_literal_value from HIR with expr_node
        Let is_number be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with expr_node, "hcl_number"
        If is_number is equal to 1:
            Note: HCL numeric literal: re-emit the exact source text unquoted.
            Return value
        End If
        Let quoted be "\""
        Set quoted to proc string_concat from StringPrim with quoted, value
        Set quoted to proc string_concat from StringPrim with quoted, "\""
        Return quoted
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BOOL_LITERAL:
        Let bool_value be proc hir_get_bool_literal_value from HIR with expr_node
        If bool_value is equal to 1:
            Return "true"
        Otherwise:
            Return "false"
        End If
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_NULL_LITERAL:
        Return "null"
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_IDENTIFIER:
        Let name be proc hir_get_identifier_name from HIR with expr_node
        Return name
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_LIST_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_array_literal with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_MAP_LITERAL:
        Return proc generate_dictionary_literal with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_BINARY_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_binary_expr with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_UNARY_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_unary_expr with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_TERNARY_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_conditional_expr with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_CALL_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_call_expr with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_MEMBER_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_member_expr with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    If expr_type is equal to HIR.HIR_INDEX_EXPR:
        Return proc generate_index_expr with ctx, expr_node
    End If

    Return "unknown"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit an HCL list literal "[a, b, c]". Used for variable defaults,
resource arrays, and any list value.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds a "[" + comma-separated elements via generate_expression + "]"
string. Returns the accumulated expression.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_array_literal" takes ctx as Integer, array_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let elements be proc hir_get_list_elements from HIR with array_node
    Let elem_count be proc list_length from ListCore with elements

    Let result be "["
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than elem_count:
        Let elem be proc list_get from ListCore with elements, i
        Let elem_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, elem
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, elem_str

        If i is less than elem_count minus 1:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, ", "
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "]"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit an HCL object literal "{ key = value, ... }". Used where HCL
expects a structured map rather than a block.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds "{ " + comma-separated "key = value" pairs via
generate_expression + " }".
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_dictionary_literal" takes ctx as Integer, dict_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let pairs be proc hir_get_map_entries from HIR with dict_node
    Let pair_count be proc list_length from ListCore with pairs

    Let result be "{\n"
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than pair_count:
        Let pair be proc list_get from ListCore with pairs, i
        Let key be proc hir_get_map_entry_key from HIR with pair
        Let value be proc hir_get_map_entry_value from HIR with pair

        Let key_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, key
        Let value_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, value

        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "  "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, key_str
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, " = "
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, value_str

        If i is less than pair_count minus 1:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "\n"
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "\n}"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit a binary expression in HCL syntax. The HIR operator must be mapped
to its HCL spelling via map_hir_operator_to_hcl since the spellings can
differ (e.g. HIR "equals" -> HCL "==").
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Recursively renders left, then concatenates " op " (where op is from
map_hir_operator_to_hcl), then right.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_binary_expr" takes ctx as Integer, binary_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let operator be proc hir_get_binary_op from HIR with binary_node
    Let left be proc hir_get_binary_left from HIR with binary_node
    Let right be proc hir_get_binary_right from HIR with binary_node

    Let left_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, left
    Let right_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, right
    Let op_str be proc map_hir_operator_to_hcl with operator

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringPrim with left_str, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, op_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, " "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, right_str

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Map a HIR operator string to the equivalent HCL operator. Most match
("+", "-", "*", "/", "%"); equality and logical operators differ
(HCL uses "==", "!=", "&&", "||" vs HIR's word-based names).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Switch-style chain of string comparisons against HIR operator names.
Returns the HCL spelling. Unknown operators fall through to a default.
@End Implementation

Process called "map_hir_operator_to_hcl" takes operator as Integer returns Integer:
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_ADD:
        Return "+"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_SUBTRACT:
        Return "-"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_MULTIPLY:
        Return "*"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_DIVIDE:
        Return "/"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_EQUAL:
        Return "=="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_NOT_EQUAL:
        Return "!="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LESS_THAN:
        Return "<"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LESS_EQUAL:
        Return "<="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_GREATER_THAN:
        Return ">"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_GREATER_EQUAL:
        Return ">="
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_AND:
        Return "&&"
    End If
    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_OR:
        Return "||"
    End If
    Return "+"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit a unary expression. HCL supports unary "-" and "!"; the operator
is mapped from HIR's spelling.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits the mapped HCL operator immediately followed by the operand
expression.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_unary_expr" takes ctx as Integer, unary_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let operator be proc hir_get_unary_op from HIR with unary_node
    Let operand be proc hir_get_unary_operand from HIR with unary_node

    Let operand_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, operand

    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_LOGICAL_NOT:
        Let result be "!"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, operand_str
        Return result
    End If

    If operator is equal to HIR.HIR_OP_NEGATE:
        Set result to "-"
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, operand_str
        Return result
    End If

    Return operand_str
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit an HCL ternary "cond ? a : b". HCL's only conditional syntax in
expression position.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Builds "cond ? then : else" by recursively rendering each branch and
concatenating with the punctuation.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_conditional_expr" takes ctx as Integer, cond_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let condition be proc hir_get_ternary_condition from HIR with cond_node
    Let true_expr be proc hir_get_ternary_then from HIR with cond_node
    Let false_expr be proc hir_get_ternary_else from HIR with cond_node

    Let cond_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, condition
    Let true_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, true_expr
    Let false_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, false_expr

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringPrim with cond_str, " ? "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, true_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, " : "
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, false_str

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit an HCL function call "name(arg1, arg2, ...)". HCL has a fixed set
of builtin functions plus provider-supplied ones; the callee name is
passed through verbatim.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Renders callee, "(", comma-separated argument expressions, ")".
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_call_expr" takes ctx as Integer, call_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let callee be proc hir_get_call_callee from HIR with call_node
    Let arguments be proc hir_get_call_arguments from HIR with call_node

    Let callee_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, callee
    Let result be proc string_concat from StringPrim with callee_str, "("

    Let arg_count be proc list_length from ListCore with arguments
    Let i be 0

    While i is less than arg_count:
        Let arg be proc list_get from ListCore with arguments, i
        Let arg_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, arg
        Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, arg_str

        If i is less than arg_count minus 1:
            Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, ", "
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, ")"
    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit HCL dotted-path access "obj.member". Common for variable
references (var.x, local.y, aws_instance.foo.id).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Renders the object expression, emits ".", emits the member name.
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_member_expr" takes ctx as Integer, member_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let object be proc hir_get_member_object from HIR with member_node
    Let member_name be proc hir_get_member_name from HIR with member_node

    Note: Check for splat operator
    Let is_splat be proc hir_get_metadata from HIR with member_node, "hcl_splat"
    If is_splat is equal to 1:
        Let object_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, object
        Let result be proc string_concat from StringPrim with object_str, ".*"
        Return result
    End If

    Set object_str to proc generate_expression with ctx, object
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with object_str, "."
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, member_name

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emit HCL bracket-index access "obj[index]". Used for list element
access and map key lookup.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Renders the object expression, emits "[", renders the index expression,
emits "]".
@End Implementation

Process called "generate_index_expr" takes ctx as Integer, index_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let object be proc hir_get_index_object from HIR with index_node
    Let index be proc hir_get_index_value from HIR with index_node

    Let object_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, object
    Let index_str be proc generate_expression with ctx, index

    Let result be proc string_concat from StringPrim with object_str, "["
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, index_str
    Set result to proc string_concat from StringPrim with result, "]"

    Return result
End Process

Note: ===================================================================
Note: PUBLIC API
Note: ===================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public alias for generate_hcl_from_hir, kept for callers that prefer
the "hir_to_target_generate" naming convention used elsewhere in the
backend tree.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls generate_hcl_from_hir and returns its result unchanged.
@End Implementation

Process called "hir_to_hcl_generate" takes hir_module as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc generate_hcl_from_hir with hir_module
End Process
